img_path = list()
races = list()
path = '/content/UTKFace'
for img in os.listdir(path):
  temp = img.split('.') # temp[0] = 26_0_0_20170117195612332
  if len(temp[0].split('_')) == 4:
    img_path.append(os.path.join(path, img))
    age, gender, race, date = temp[0].split('_')
    races.append(int(race))
  else:
    continue

class_labels = {0:"White", 1:"Black",2:"Asian", 3:"Indian", 4:"Others"}
races_list = [ list(to_categorical(i, len(class_labels))) for i in races]
races = [ str(to_categorical(i, len(class_labels))) for i in races]

Phase 1 Part 6:¶

As mentioned in previous projects, there are 2 way to approach.

  • Label encoding has the advantage that it is straightforward but it has the disadvantage that the numeric values can be “misinterpreted” by the algorithms. For example, the value of 0 is obviously less than the value of 4 but does that really correspond to the data set in real life? Does a wagon have “4X” more weight in our calculation than the convertible? In this example, I don’t think so.

  • A common alternative approach is called one hot encoding. Despite the different names, the basic strategy is to convert each category value into a new column and assigns a 1 or 0 (True/False) value to the column. ---> One-Hot has the benefit of not weighting a value improperly but does have the downside of adding more columns to the data set.

Answer to one question: Parameters¶

Total params: 10,832,133. It is obvious that in neural networks we have "Weights" and "Bias" and in each layer there is a matrix with nm enteries (n is the size of input of layer and m is the size of output of layer) so we have nm parameters for weiht of each layer and we have m for the bias

def get_proper_class(TestData_classes, y_pred_test, TrainData_classes, y_pred_train):
  y_pred_train_show = []
  TrainData_classes_show = []
  y_pred_test_show = []
  TestData_classes_show = []

  for i in range(len(y_pred_train)):
    if(y_pred_train[i]== 4):
      y_pred_train_show.append(0)
    if(y_pred_train[i]== 3):
      y_pred_train_show.append(1)
    if(y_pred_train[i]== 2):
      y_pred_train_show.append(2)
    if(y_pred_train[i]== 1):
      y_pred_train_show.append(3)
    if(y_pred_train[i]== 0):
      y_pred_train_show.append(4)
    
    if(TrainData_classes[i]== 4):
      TrainData_classes_show.append(0)
    if(TrainData_classes[i]== 3):
      TrainData_classes_show.append(1)
    if(TrainData_classes[i]== 2):
      TrainData_classes_show.append(2)
    if(TrainData_classes[i]== 1):
      TrainData_classes_show.append(3)
    if(TrainData_classes[i]== 0):
      TrainData_classes_show.append(4)

  for i in range(len(y_pred_test)):
    if(y_pred_test[i]== 4):
      y_pred_test_show.append(0)
    if(y_pred_test[i]== 3):
      y_pred_test_show.append(1)
    if(y_pred_test[i]== 2):
      y_pred_test_show.append(2)
    if(y_pred_test[i]== 1):
      y_pred_test_show.append(3)
    if(y_pred_test[i]== 0):
      y_pred_test_show.append(4)
    
    if(TestData_classes[i]== 4):
      TestData_classes_show.append(0)
    if(TestData_classes[i]== 3):
      TestData_classes_show.append(1)
    if(TestData_classes[i]== 2):
      TestData_classes_show.append(2)
    if(TestData_classes[i]== 1):
      TestData_classes_show.append(3)
    if(TestData_classes[i]== 0):
      TestData_classes_show.append(4)
  return TestData_classes_show, y_pred_test_show, TrainData_classes_show, y_pred_train_show

input = layers.Input(shape=(100, 100, 1)) #Gray scale 
output = layers.Flatten()(input)
output = layers.Dense(1024, activation="relu")(output)
output = layers.Dense(512, activation="relu")(output)
output = layers.Dense(128, activation="relu")(output)
output = layers.Dense(5, activation="softmax")(output)

Phase 3: Classification:¶

Part 1: Optimizers¶

PDF FILE next to this file 4 parts¶

  • In the PDF FIle I have explained What adam and momentum benefits are and explained about them.

  • After running with momentum 0.5 and 0.9 we can see that

    • momentum 0.5: Accuracy F1 = 73%
    • momentum 0.9: Accuracy F1 = 68% -> This thells us that with momentum 0.5 we got a better result

  • We can totally see that the answer to this question is "NO", because instead of taking leading to faster converging it may start to diverge from optimal solution

  • In the PDF FIle I have explained What adam benefits is and explained about it. After running with adam we can see that

    • Adam: Accuracy F1 = 74% (for train) -> This thells us that with adam we get a good result and we will continue with this

Part 2: Epochs¶

  • We will train with 20 epochs

  • Question: Why do we need to perform our learning algorith in several epochs?

    • Because the most common method for training in deep learning is a form of gradient descent. Each epoch finds the approximate direction that each parameter needs to be adjusted but it's just approximate. If you adjust too much in one epoch you will overshoot the set of parameters you're actually trying to find.

  • Question: Is it always better to have more epochs?

    • NO, the algorithm may overfit on training DATA and can't get generalized on test data. large epochs may lead to huge error on test data.

  • Question: What should we do ?

    • A very special way to deal with this types of situations, is "VALIDATION AND STOP". in this way we would make a validation test on the epoch we are entering if the result was not satisfactory, we would cease the operation,
    • Another way to do it is to define a threshhold that we desire and when it made the difference between highest accuracy and present accuracy, it will cease the operation.

Part 3: Loss function¶

  • We can totally complrehend that MSE should not be better loss function for classification (In this implementation we got a better accuracy)

  • There are two reasons why Mean Squared Error(MSE) is a bad choice for binary classification problems:

    • First, using MSE means that we assume that the underlying data has been generated from a normal distribution (a bell-shaped curve). In Bayesian terms this means we assume a Gaussian prior. While in reality, a dataset that can be classified into two categories (i.e binary) is not from a normal distribution but a Bernoulli distribution (Check out the answer to “Where did the Binary Cross-Entropy Loss Function come from?” for more details and also for an intro to maximum likelihood estimation).

    • Secondly, the MSE function is non-convex for binary classification. In simple terms, if a binary classification model is trained with MSE Cost function, it is not guaranteed to minimize the Cost function. This is because MSE function expects real-valued inputs in range(-∞, ∞), while binary classification models output probabilities in range(0,1) through the sigmoid/logistic function.

  • When do we have to use MSE:

    • he ideal MSE isn't 0, since then you would have a model that perfectly predicts your training data, but which is very unlikely to perfectly predict any other data. What you want is a balance between overfit (very low MSE for training data) and underfit (very high MSE for test/validation/unseen data).

source -> towardsdatascience

Part 4: regularization¶

  • Regularizers allow you to apply penalties on layer parameters or layer activity during optimization. These penalties are summed into the loss function that the network optimizes.
  • L2 regulization
    • L2 regularization adds an L2 penalty equal to the square of the magnitude of coefficients. L2 will not yield sparse models and all coefficients are shrunk by the same factor (none are eliminated). -> RESULT: 
       for train accuracy:  75%    18964
 for test accuracy:   72%    4741
 -> Good but not way better
  • Dropout is a regularization
    • method that approximates training a large number of neural networks with different architectures in parallel.During training, some number of layer outputs are randomly ignored or “dropped out.” This has the effect of making the layer look-like and be treated-like a layer with a different number of nodes and connectivity to the prior layer. In effect, each update to a layer during training is performed with a different “view” of the configured layer. -> RESULT: 
       for train accuracy:  54%     18964
 for test accuracy:   54%      4741
 -> It was NOT wise to put Dropout in all the layers. It was better to only put them in some layers.

regularizers.l2¶

from tensorflow.keras import regularizers
# from tensorflow.keras import layers
import tensorflow as tf
input = layers.Input(shape=(100, 100, 1)) #Gray scale 
output = layers.Flatten()(input)

output = layers.Dense(1024, activation="relu", kernel_regularizer=regularizers.l2(l2=1e-4))(output)
output = layers.Dense(512, activation="relu", kernel_regularizer=regularizers.l2(l2=1e-4))(output)
output = layers.Dense(128, activation="relu", kernel_regularizer=regularizers.l2(l2=1e-4))(output)

output = layers.Dense(5, activation="softmax")(output)

model = models.Model(inputs = input, outputs = output)
model.compile(optimizer='Adam', loss = "categorical_crossentropy", metrics=["accuracy"])
history = model.fit(TrainData, validation_data=TestData, epochs = 20)

Dropout all layers¶

In [46]:
input = layers.Input(shape=(100, 100, 1)) #Gray scale 
output = layers.Flatten()(input)

output = layers.Dense(1024, activation="relu")(output)
output = layers.Dropout(0.1)(output)
output = layers.Dense(512, activation="relu")(output)
output = layers.Dropout(0.1)(output)
output = layers.Dense(128, activation="relu")(output)
output = layers.Dropout(0.1)(output)

output = layers.Dense(5, activation="softmax")(output)

model = models.Model(inputs = input, outputs = output)
model.compile(optimizer='Adam', loss = "categorical_crossentropy", metrics=["accuracy"])
history = model.fit(TrainData, validation_data=TestData, epochs = 20)

from tensorflow.keras import regularizers
# from tensorflow.keras import layers
import tensorflow as tf

input = layers.Input(shape=(100, 100, 1)) #Gray scale 
output = layers.Flatten()(input)

#Encoder - Begin
output = layers.Dense(10000, activation="relu", kernel_regularizer=regularizers.l2(l2=1e-4))(output)
output = layers.Dense(1024, activation="relu", kernel_regularizer=regularizers.l2(l2=1e-4))(output)
output = layers.Dense(512, activation="relu", kernel_regularizer=regularizers.l2(l2=1e-4))(output)
output = layers.Dense(64, activation="relu", kernel_regularizer=regularizers.l2(l2=1e-4))(output)
output = layers.Dense(32, activation="relu", kernel_regularizer=regularizers.l2(l2=1e-4))(output)
output2 = layers.Dense(2, activation="relu", kernel_regularizer=regularizers.l2(l2=1e-4))(output)

#Encoder - End
output = layers.Dense(5, activation="softmax")(output2)

model = models.Model(inputs = input, outputs = output, name='encoder')
model.compile(optimizer='Adam', loss = "categorical_crossentropy", metrics=["accuracy"])
history = model.fit(TrainData, validation_data=TestData, epochs = 20)

z_mean = layers.Dense(latent_dim)(h)
z_log_sigma = layers.Dense(latent_dim)(h)
In [75]:
from keras import backend as K

def sampling(args):
    z_mean, z_log_sigma = args
    epsilon = K.random_normal(shape=(K.shape(z_mean)[0], latent_dim),
                              mean=0., stddev=0.1)
    return z_mean + K.exp(z_log_sigma) * epsilon

z = layers.Lambda(sampling)([z_mean, z_log_sigma])

# Create encoder
encoder = Model(inputs, [z_mean, z_log_sigma], name='encoder')

# Create decoder
latent_inputs = Input(shape=(latent_dim,), name='z_sampling')
x = layers.Dense(intermediate_dim, activation='relu')(latent_inputs)
outputs = layers.Dense(original_dim, activation='sigmoid')(x)
decoder = Model(latent_inputs, outputs, name='decoder')

# instantiate VAE model
outputs = decoder(encoder(inputs)[1])
vae = Model(inputs, outputs, name='vae_mlp')
In [88]:
reconstruction_loss = losses.binary_crossentropy(inputs, outputs)
reconstruction_loss *= original_dim
kl_loss = 1 + z_log_sigma - K.square(z_mean) - K.exp(z_log_sigma)
kl_loss = K.sum(kl_loss, axis=-1)
kl_loss *= -0.5
vae_loss = K.mean(reconstruction_loss + kl_loss)
vae.add_loss(vae_loss)
vae.compile(optimizer='adam')
